From $\frac{\partial x^{\prime \mu}}{\partial x^{\alpha}} = \delta_{\alpha}^{\mu} + \varepsilon_{\ , \alpha}^{\mu}$, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
g_{\mu \nu}^{\prime}\left(x^{\prime}\right) &= \frac{\partial x^{\prime \alpha}}{\partial x^{\mu}} \frac{\partial x^{\prime \beta}}{\partial x^{\nu}} g_{\alpha \beta}(x) = \left(\delta_{\mu}^{\alpha} + \varepsilon_{,\mu}^{\alpha}\right)\left(\delta_{\nu}^{\beta} + \varepsilon_{,\nu}^{\beta}\right) g_{\alpha \beta}(x) \\
& \approx g_{\mu \nu}(x) + g_{\alpha \nu}(x) \varepsilon_{,\mu}^{\alpha} + g_{\mu \beta}(x) \varepsilon_{,\nu}^{\beta}
\end{aligned}
$$

Using the Taylor expansion, we obtain

$$
g_{\mu \nu}^{\prime}\left(x^{\prime}\right) = g_{\mu \nu}(x) + g_{\mu \nu,\alpha}(x) \varepsilon^{\alpha}
$$

Thus,

$$
g_{\mu \nu}^{\prime}(x) = g_{\mu \nu}(x) - g_{\mu \nu,\alpha}(x) \varepsilon^{\alpha} + g_{\alpha \nu}(x) \varepsilon_{,\mu}^{\alpha} + g_{\mu \beta}(x) \varepsilon_{,\nu}^{\beta}
$$

However, since $g_{\mu \nu}^{\prime} = \eta_{\mu \nu} + h_{\mu \nu}^{\prime}$, it follows that $h_{\mu \nu}^{\prime} = h_{\mu \nu} + \varepsilon_{\mu,\nu} + \varepsilon_{\nu,\mu}$. From the field equation

$$
\square h_{\mu \nu} = \theta_{\mu,\nu} + \theta_{\nu,\mu}
$$

we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\square h_{\mu \nu}^{\prime} &= \theta_{\mu,\nu} + \theta_{\nu,\mu} + \square \varepsilon_{\mu,\nu} + \square \varepsilon_{\nu,\mu} \\
&= \theta_{\mu,\nu}^{\prime} + \theta_{\nu,\mu}^{\prime} - \varepsilon_{,\alpha \alpha \nu} - \square \varepsilon_{\mu,\nu} + \frac{1}{2} \varepsilon_{,\alpha,\nu} + \frac{1}{2} \varepsilon_{,\alpha \alpha \nu}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& - \varepsilon_{,\nu \alpha \alpha} - \square \varepsilon_{\nu,\mu} + \frac{1}{2} \varepsilon_{,\alpha,\mu} + \frac{1}{2} \varepsilon_{,\alpha \alpha \mu} + \square \varepsilon_{\mu,\nu} + \square \varepsilon_{\nu,\mu} \\
= & \theta_{\mu,\nu}^{\prime} + \theta_{\nu,\mu}^{\prime}
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, it satisfies gauge invariance.

When the observer moves with velocity \( v \), the transformations of the electric field and the magnetic field are given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
\boldsymbol{E}^{\prime} & =\gamma\left(\boldsymbol{E}+\frac{\boldsymbol{v}}{c} \times \boldsymbol{H}\right)-(\gamma-1) \frac{\boldsymbol{v} \cdot \boldsymbol{E}}{v^{2}} \boldsymbol{v}, \\
\boldsymbol{H}^{\prime} & =\gamma\left(\boldsymbol{H}-\frac{\boldsymbol{v}}{c} \times \boldsymbol{E}\right)-(\gamma-1) \frac{\boldsymbol{v} \cdot \boldsymbol{H}}{v^{2}} \boldsymbol{v}
\end{aligned}
$$

Since \(\boldsymbol{E} \cdot \boldsymbol{H}=0\) is an invariant and \(\boldsymbol{E}^{\prime} \cdot \boldsymbol{H}^{\prime}=0\), it follows that \(\left|\boldsymbol{E}^{\prime} \times \boldsymbol{H}^{\prime}\right|^{2}=\left|\boldsymbol{E}^{\prime}\right|^{2}\left|\boldsymbol{H}^{\prime}\right|^{2}-\left(\boldsymbol{E}^{\prime} \cdot \boldsymbol{H}^{\prime}\right)^{2} = \left|\boldsymbol{E}^{\prime}\right|^{2}\left|\boldsymbol{H}^{\prime}\right|^{2}\). Substituting the expressions for \(\boldsymbol{E}^{\prime}\) and \(\boldsymbol{H}^{\prime}\) and simplifying yields

$$
\left|\boldsymbol{S}^{\prime}\right|=\frac{\left(1-v_{//} / c\right)^{2}}{1-v^{2} / c^{2}}|\boldsymbol{S}|=\frac{\left(1-v_{//} / c\right)^{2}}{1-\left(v_{//}^{2}+v_{\perp}^{2}\right) / c^{2}} \frac{L}{4 \pi r^{2}}
$$

This is the energy flux measured by the observer.

Refer to Figure 5.2. Assume that mirrors \( A \) and \( B \) are separated by a distance \( L \). In the stationary frame, the round-trip time for light is \( t_{0} = \frac{2L}{c} \), which is the time for one tick of the clock when it is stationary. The time for one tick when the clock is moving is \( t_{0}^{\prime} \), as shown in Figure 5.2. We have

\[
