& t_{0}^{\prime} = \frac{2L}{\sqrt{c^{2} - v^{2}}} = \frac{2L}{c} \frac{1}{\sqrt{1 - v^{2} / c^{2}}} = \frac{t_{0}}{\sqrt{1 - v^{2} / c^{2}}}
\end{aligned}
\]

The solution involves the fact that since the \( S^{\prime} \) frame moves along the \( x \) axis of the \( S \) frame, the projection of the meter stick in the \( y \) direction is equal to its projection in the \( y^{\prime} \) direction. This can be expressed as:

\[
\begin{aligned}
l \sin \alpha & = l^{\prime} \sin \alpha^{\prime} = 1 \cdot \sin 30^{\circ} = 0.5 \, \mathrm{m}, \\
l & = \frac{0.5}{\sin \alpha} = \frac{0.5}{\sin 45^{\circ}} \approx 0.707 \, \mathrm{m}
\end{aligned}
\]

Therefore, the length of the meter stick as measured in the \( S \) frame is approximately \( 0.707 \, \mathrm{m} \).

