If the photon undergoes elastic backscattering, the momenta of the photon and the particle after scattering are $-p_{1}$ and $p_{2}$, respectively. From the conservation of energy and momentum during the scattering process, we have:

$$
\begin{gathered}
p_{1} c+\sqrt{p_{2}^{2} c^{2}+m^{2} c^{4}}=p c+m c^{2} \\
-p_{1}+p_{2}=p
\end{gathered}
$$

By eliminating $p_{2}$, we obtain

$$
\begin{gathered}
\left(p-p_{1}\right)^{2}+2\left(p-p_{1}\right) m c=\left(p+p_{1}\right)^{2} \\
p_{1}=\frac{m c p}{2 p+m c}
\end{gathered}
$$

This is the magnitude of the momentum of the photon after backscattering in the laboratory frame.

